baseline_groups.claim_summary: ITT effect of Medicaid lottery selection on employment and earnings. Oregon Health Insurance Experiment lottery as random assignment, with lottery-draw FE and lagged outcome controls, probability weights, clustered at household (reservation_id).
baseline_groups.notes: Three baseline outcomes from Table 1: any_earn2009 (primary), earn2009, earn_ab_fpl_adj_2009. All use same specification: treatment + nnn* + lagged_outcome, pw=weight_ssa_admin, cluster(reservation_id). Data is synthetic (SSA admin data not publicly available). Baseline coefficient reported is for the primary outcome any_earn2009.

baseline_groups.claim_summary: ITT effect of Medicaid lottery selection on government benefit receipt (SNAP, TANF, SSI, SSDI). Same design as G1: lottery-draw FE, lagged outcome controls, probability weights, clustered at household.
baseline_groups.notes: Eight baseline outcomes from Table 2: four binary indicators (any SNAP, TANF, SSI, DI) and four amounts. All use same specification as G1. Baseline coefficient reported is for the primary outcome any_snapamt2009.

global_notes: No changes to baseline group assignments relative to the surface. The surface correctly identified two baseline groups: G1 (earnings/employment, Table 1) and G2 (government benefits, Table 2). Data is synthetic since the SSA administrative records are restricted-access. Two alternative outcome specs (any_wage2009, any_se2009) produce identical estimates to the baseline any_earn2009, likely because synthetic data used the same variable -- these are flagged as potentially invalid.
